Data

These lines of code extract the City of Fairfax Police Departments Calls for Service

id.calls <- "1gRoL7lZlwm7sreA5F9WbPoH5su4n4iGS"
calls.temp <- read.csv(sprintf("https://docs.google.com/uc?id=%s&export=download", id.calls))

Data Cleansing

This section of code cleans the call table utilized in this project by formatting the dates, creating a day of week column, and a month of year column

calls.temp$date <- as.Date(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$dow <- weekdays(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$day <- day(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$month <- substr(calls.temp$date, 6, 7)

Subseting the Data

Here I chose to analyze 911-hang-up calls as my specfic call for service

calls.type <- calls.temp %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))
calls <- subset(calls.temp, calls.temp$type == '911 HANG-UP')

Calculating Basic Statistics

These lines of code represent statistical data which helped to reveal baseline measurements including the first (2007-01-02) and last known call (2023-04-30), as well as the highest amount of calls per day (7), and the least (0).

calls.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(count = n())


first <- min(calls.day$date)
last <- max(calls.day$date)


calls.day <- calls.day %>% 
  complete(date = seq(ymd(first), 
                      ymd(last), 
                      "day")) %>%
  mutate(dow = wday(date, label = T, week_start = 1), 
         month.name = month(date, label = T, abbr = F),
         month.num = substr(date, 6,7),
         week = isoweek(date),
         day = day(date),
         year = year(date))


calls.day$count[is.na(calls.day$count)] = "0"
calls.day$count <- as.numeric(calls.day$count)


high <- as.numeric(max(calls.day$count))
low <- as.numeric(min(calls.day$count))
mean <- mean(calls.day$count)
sd <- sd(calls.day$count)

These lines of code pertain to the temporal typologies and help sort calls by the different units of time measurement (hour of day, day of week, month of year, year)

calls.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'dow'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.
calls.day.time <- subset(calls.day.time, !is.na(calls.day.time$hour))
calls.year.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'dow'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.day.time <- subset(calls.year.day.time, !is.na(calls.year.day.time$hour))

Analysis

The analysis is broken into four sections, each concentrating on different units of time measurement in relation to 911-hang-up call hotspots and coldspots. The first section discusses month of year hot spots and cold spots, as well as what to expect in August 2023. The following section highlights day of week hotspots and coldspots and what can be expected to occur call wise next week. Then, hour of day hotspots, coldspots, trends, and patterns are discussed. Finally, the last section remarks on how hotspots and coldspots fluctuate and remain consistent throughout these units of measurement.

Hotspots and Coldspots by the Months

calls.year.month <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.month <- subset(calls.year.month, !is.na(calls.year.month$month))

graph2 <- ggplot(calls.year.month, aes(year, month, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white", lwd = .5, linetype = 1) + 
  geom_text(aes(label = count), color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  coord_fixed()

graph2 + labs(x = "Year", y = "Month", title = "Months by Year", caption = "Source: ...") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2007:2023)) +
  theme_minimal()

This upcoming August I predict there to be an increase in 911 hang up calls in line with previous August year trends. Not only did August of ’22 accrue the highest amount of 911 hang up calls (64), August of ’21 was as well one of the top receiving call months (41). So far, January-March of 2023 calls have been on trend with their previous years call rates so I predict for August to be a hot month for calls. I do however not believe it likely for the number of 911 hang up calls to occur this August to be as drastic but rather be in the same ballpark, possibly even lesser. I say this because no other month of any other year has ever come close to reaching the 60s for calls, that said I believe this to have been a stand out anomalie. Calls by month also appear to be dropping and lesser than they were in 2022 by each month (calls decreased from 37 February of ’22 to 16 in ’23).

One interesting observation is that despite some months consistently having lower numbers of 911 hang up calls than others, 911 hang up calls have appeared to become more prevalent consistently throughout each month since 2020. November and December for instance never surpassed that of 25 calls in a given year until 2020 when November climaxed at (44) calls and December at (46) calls. Despite this finding, it is clear that January, February, June, and November are colder months compared to the rest as they more consistently than others result in the lowest count of calls across the board (predominantly purple boxes). Not including 911 hang up calls occurring in 2023, November is the coldest of the months with (271) combined calls from 2007-2021, closely followed by January with (276) total calls.

As can be seen by the graph displayed above, hot spot months are harder to single out as a whole, requiring a count of each row to be conducted. This count revealed August to be the hottest month with (362) total calls, followed by July with (338). Interestingly, April, May, October, March, September, and December were all close in count ranging from 301-315 calls per month total.

calls.day <- mutate(calls.day, 
                    week = case_when(month.name == "December" & week == 1 ~ 53,
                                     month.name == "January" & week %in% 52:53 ~ 0,
                                     TRUE ~ week),
                    category = cut(count, c(low-1, (mean-sd*3), (mean-sd*2), (mean-sd), mean, (mean+sd), (mean+sd*2), (mean+sd*3), high+1))) 

calls.summary <- calls.day %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

Hotspots and Coldspots by the days of the week

ggplot(calls.day, aes(x= count)) + geom_histogram(fill = "purple") +
  geom_vline(data = calls.day, aes(xintercept = mean(count)), linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +
  facet_wrap(~ dow, nrow = 4)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

As can be seen in the first bar graph above, at first glance it is very hard to distinguish at which days of the week hot spots and cold spots are present. However, an overall analysis of all the various graphs in this project reveal Saturday and Sunday to be the most obvious days of cold spots with no major hot spots appearing at any hour throughout the duration of these two days (refer to the hours of day graph). Sunday takes place as the number one cold spot day of the week followed closely by Saturday. The two hottest days of the week are Thursday and Friday, with Thursday being the hotter of the two. This finding helps to support an earlier statement of 4pm on Thursdays being one of the most central hotspots. In-between these major hotspots and cold spots are Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday where each respective day has obvious hotspots throughout the day, but also some colder spots too which keep them at in-between states. As it goes for next week, I predict for the weekend to start on a calm note Saturday and Sunday with very few to possibly no calls as the high for any given day for 911 hang up calls is 7 and the low is 0. That said, I predict for 2-3 calls at most to occur next weekend. Following the weekend I believe calls will start to pick up yet still remain low overall as 911 hang up calls do not necessarily occur every day and when they do, they occur at low rates. That said, I believe on average about one call will occur per weekday next week. I also believe that if any day receives multiple calls, it will be Thursday as that is the hottest of the days for 911 hang up calls.

Hotspots and Coldspots by the Hours of the Day

graph <- ggplot(calls.day.time, aes(hour, dow, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile(color = "black", lwd = .5, linetype = 1) + 
  geom_text(aes(label = count), color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  coord_fixed()

graph1 <- ggplot(calls.day.time, aes(hour, dow, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile() + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +
  guides(fill = guide_colourbar(title = "Call Activity")) +
  theme_classic() +
  coord_fixed()

graph1 + 
  labs(x = "Hour of Day", y = "Day of Week", title = "Hour of Day by Day of Week") +
  scale_y_discrete(limits = c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday")) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0:23))

To my surprise, 911 hang up call hour of day hotspots are not in the early morning hours at and past midnight but rather between 11am-8pm. 4pm appears to be the prime time for 911 hang up calls to occur as can be noticed in the graph displayed above, with Tuesday-Thursday as the hottest days. Revealing 4pm Tuesdays-Thursdays to be the prime for 911 hang up calls to occur. The coldest of hour of day cold spots are likewise lumped together between 11pm-7am. 4am is the coldest spot with (82) calls total, followed by 5am with (83) calls and 3am with (85) calls. The reoccurring pattern that is likely to continue is for these 911 hang up calls to mostly occur during broad daylight and predominately between 12pm-4pm. With 16 years worth of data reflecting these calls to most heavily occur during the earlier afternoon, it is very likely that there will not be a major influx of 912 hang up calls at the later evening and early morning hours between 11pm-8am.

Concluding Thoughts

calls.year.month.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, month, day) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.month.day <- subset(calls.year.month.day, !is.na(calls.year.month.day$day))

graph3 <- ggplot(calls.year.month.day, aes(day, month, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white", lwd = .5, linetype = 1) + 
  geom_text(aes(label = count), color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  coord_fixed()

graph3 + labs(x = "Day", y = "Month", title = "Day of Month / Month of Year", caption = "Source: ...") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(01-12)) +
  theme_minimal()

With 911 hang up calls being capable of occurring for a handful of reasons, I believe that hot spots and cold spots are likely to change across and over time for this specific call for service. One thing that was quite consistent, or clear, throughout all these visuals was August being a prime hot spot month, Tuesday-Thursday being the hottest days, and 12pm-5pm being the hottest hours. Another consistent finding was Saturday and Sundays being cold spot days, 12am-7am being cold spot times, and November and January being the coldest of the 12 months. The four months of 2023 data captured in this analysis help to make the presumption that hotspots and cold spots are changing over time for 911 hang up calls. 911 hang up calls were not such a phenomenon until 2020. Since 2020 hot spots have started to quickly emerge and will likely continue to remain or increase this coming year if the rest of the 8 months not captured in this years data are in line with the 4 that have been captured.
